#: src/view/builder.md:83
msgid "Using Components with the Builder Syntax"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:85
msgid ""
"To create your own components with the builder syntax, you can simply use "
"plain functions (see above). To use other components (for example, the built-"
"in `For` or `Show` control-flow components), you can take advantage of the "
"fact that each component is a function of one component props argument, and "
"component props have their own builder."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:87
msgid "You can either use the component props builder:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:96 src/view/builder.md:111
msgid "\"I will appear if `value` is 5 or lower\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:98 src/view/builder.md:112
msgid "\"I will appear if `value` is above 5\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:103
msgid "or you can directly build the props struct:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:115
msgid ""
"Using the component builder correctly applies the various modifiers like "
"`#[prop(into)]`; using the struct syntax, we’ve applied this manually by "
"calling `.into()` ourselves."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:117
msgid "Expanding Macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/builder.md:119
msgid ""
"Not every feature of the `view` macro or `component` macro syntax has been "
"described here in detail. However, Rust provides you the tools you need to "
"understand what is going on with any macro. Specifically, rust-analyzer’s "
"[\"expand macro recursively\" feature](https://rust-analyzer.github.io/book/"
"features.html#expand-macro-recursively) allows you to expand any macro to "
"show the code it generates, and [`cargo-expand`](https://crates.io/crates/"
"cargo-expand) expands all the macros in a project into regular Rust code. "
"The rest of this book will continue using the `view` macro syntax, but if "
"you’re ever unsure how to translate this into the builder syntax, you can "
"use these tools to explore the code that is generated."
msgstr ""
